parse: Interrogative / Indefinite Pronoun - Nominative Masculine Singular
str2: Who, which, what, why. Probably emphatic of tis; an interrogative pronoun, who, which or what.
Therefore, then. Apparently a primary word; certainly, or accordingly.

parse: Verb - Present Indicative Active - 3rd Person Singular
str2: I am, exist. The first person singular present indicative; a prolonged form of a primary and defective verb; I exist.

parse: Personal / Possessive Pronoun - Genitive 1st Person Singular
str2: I, the first-person pronoun. A primary pronoun of the first person I.
(a) pay, wages, salary, (b) reward, recompense, punishment. Apparently a primary word; pay for service, good or bad.
In order that, so that. Probably from the same as the former part of heautou; in order that.

parse: Verb - Present Participle Middle - Nominative Masculine Singular
str2: From eu and aggelos; to announce good news especially the gospel.

parse: Verb - Aorist Subjunctive Active - 1st Person Singular
str2: To put, place, lay, set, fix, establish. A prolonged form of a primary theo to place.
From the same as euaggelizo; a good message, i.e. The gospel.
Without expense, for which nothing has to be paid. Costless, i.e. Gratuitous.
A primary preposition; to or into, of place, time, or purpose; also in adverbial phrases.
Not, lest. A primary particle of qualified negation; not, lest; also (whereas ou expects an affirmative one) whether.
To use to the full, use up. From kata and chraomai; to overuse, i.e. Misuse.

parse: Personal / Possessive Pronoun - Genitive 1st Person Singular
str2: I, the first-person pronoun. A primary pronoun of the first person I.
From exesti; privilege, i.e. force, capacity, competency, freedom, or mastery, delegated influence.
In, on, among. A primary preposition denoting position, and instrumentality, i.e. A relation of rest; 'in, ' at, on, by, etc.
The, the definite article. Including the feminine he, and the neuter to in all their inflections; the definite article; the.
From the same as euaggelizo; a good message, i.e. The gospel.
